T1  - Black and Brown Tumbling the Walls Together
AN  - 2017355033
AB  - During the 1960s, intersections emerged between Mexican American activists and African American activists that informed social and education-al reform efforts in the US. On behalf of their communities, Chicana/o and African American activists sought to break down the barriers to higher education that kept Mexican American and African American youth constituencies out. In this article, intersectoral refers to the points of contact and interactions where Mexican American and African American educational sectors came together to benefit their communities jointly or respectively. While studies of relations between African American and Mexican American communities often highlight conflict or collaboration as organizing principles, this article seeks to identify where organizing efforts and advocacy intersected between these constituencies but also where influences and ideologies conjoined their social critiques. This article provides an analysis of the interstitial moments of interethnic solidarities between African American and Chicana/o student and community activists in their efforts to establish cultural centers and ethnic studies programs at UCLA in 1968.
